title: Code/Coffee/Cohort Learning The Analytics Edge
description:
Come to our weekly Code/Coffee.

We will also start a new series of cohort learning! A new semester of MIT's The Analytics Edge (https://www.edx.org/course/analytics-edge-mitx-15-071x-0) just started and this is a good way to learn data science and R. The course is well reviewed and includes a practical kaggle competition. If you are a new R user, this would be good place to begin!

Come get your hands dirty in R!

Currently these meetups are for self identified women and gender queer folks. Watch for future co-ed meetups!

title: Intro to Machine Learning with R
description:
Come to out next meetup where we will go through a machine learning tutorial using Kaggle's Titantic dataset. We can pick from several tutorials: https://www.kaggle.com/c/titanic/details/new-getting-started-with-r

I'm leaning towards Curt Wehrley's tutorial right now. https://github.com/wehrley/wehrley.github.io/blob/master/SOUPTONUTS.md

Pizza will be sponsored by Revolution Analytics. Our good friends at MAKE will be donating us their space.

title: Code and Coffee: Data Viz
description:
Come to our next Code and Coffee! This one will be focused on data viz!

Bring a data set that you want to visualize! If you don't have one, let's find one together!

title: Beginner's Walkthrough With R
description:
Wanna get started in R but don't know how? Come join us as we do an introduction to R.

Topics covered:

• Quick Intro to R Studio

• Data types

• Programming basics

• Functions/packages

• Basic plots (ggplot2)

Homework before class:

- Install R ( https://github.com/rladiestc/wiki/wiki/Installing-R)

- Understand a bit of programming basics (loops, data structures, variables) will be helpful but not required.

description:

10:15 - 10:30 Untalks if someone has something?

10:30 - 12:00 Problem solving, bring your projects, issues, and general knowledge. This is time to self organize and work on something.

title: Communicating Your Data Science Results and Wrangling Data
description:
WHAT WE'RE DOING:

You’ll learn to use R Markdown to communicate your data science results easily. Your end product will be a website (html), Word doc, or a pdf. You’ll also learn to use R package dplyr to wrangle your data; this includes making and/or transforming variables. After the demos, we'll have some time to chat and try out our new skills.

WHAT TO BRING:

Bring your laptop. Your laptop cord and a notebook might be a good idea, too. If you can, try to install R, R Studio, and the dplyr package before coming.

VOLUNTEERS:

Amanda Doan will demonstrate how to use R Markdown and Katie Jolly will teach us how to use dplyr.

CONSUMING THINGS:

Just down the hall is a mini coffee shop. (Bring your own mug to get 25 cents off!) Feel free to bring snackies or beverages from home.

LOCATION:

Meet us in room 226 of O'Shaughnessy Science (OSS). This is connected to Owens and is part of the Frey Science Center (big cement sign out front). OSS is on the west side of Cretin between Grand and Summit. The east side of the building has an elevator and the building is ADA accessible.

PARKING:

You can park on Summit for free. The parking ramp (on Grand and Cretin) is very close to OSS and is decently priced ($1.00 or $1.50 per hour).

title: Building Interactive Plots with Shiny
description:
WHAT WE'RE DOING:

This event will be a mix of socializing and trying out Shiny. Shiny is an R package that makes it easy to build interactive web apps straight from R. You can host standalone apps on a webpage or embed them in R Markdown (http://rmarkdown.rstudio.com/) documents or build dashboards (http://rstudio.github.io/shinydashboard/). Here's an example of a Shiny app (https://dgrtwo.shinyapps.io/cranview/) from David Robinson (the stats guy, not the basketball player).

WHAT TO BRING:

Bring your laptop. Your laptop cord and a notebook might be a good idea, too. If you can, try to install R and the Shiny package before coming.

CONSUMING THINGS:

Just down the hall is a mini coffee shop (open til 8PM). Feel free to bring snackies or beverages.

LOCATION:

We have a classroom for this meetup! Meet us in room 226 of O'Shaughnessy Science. This is the building connected to Owens science. You can park on Summit for free. The parking ramp is also convenient and decently priced ($1.00 or $1.50 per hour). The east side of the building has an elevator and the building is generally accessible.

VOLUNTEERS:

Kim Ky and Becca will be creating some basic examples to teach us how Shiny works.

title: Data Visualization
description:
WHAT WE'RE DOING:

This event will be a mix of socializing and data visualization. If you don't have a lot of experience with R, data viz is a fun way to get going. I think we will cover plotting in base R and get into ggplot a bit. I'm happy to add another topic if you have any ideas! This is a safe, non-competitive environment to try new things.

WHAT TO BRING:

Bring your laptop. Your laptop cord and a notebook might be a good idea, too. If you have any cool data sets, bring 'em!

CONSUMING THINGS:

Just down the hall is a mini coffee shop. You can get your espresso, drip coffee, tea, and other snacks there for cheap. (Bring your own mug and you get $0.25 off!)

LOCATION:

We have a classroom for this meetup! Meet us in room 226 of O'Shaughnessy Science. This is the building connected to Owens science. You can park on Summit for free. The parking ramp is also convenient and decently priced ($1.00 or $1.50 per hour). The east side of the building has an elevator and the building is generally accessible.

VOLUNTEERS:

Who wants to volunteer to help out with the content for this meetup? Remember, this is a safe environment for pushing yourself. I'm visualizing (ha.) you finding a data set, creating code that produces a few important types of plots, and coming up with a list of challenges (e.g. "create a plot that demonstrates the difference in bitterness between different types of beer."). Someone (maybe YOU?) can prepare materials for plotting in base R (e.g. plot, boxplot) and another person (Katie Jolly) will prepare some materials for ggplot.

title: Come say hello!
description:
Let's get to know one another!

We hope to learn how you use R, what you already know, what you'd like to learn, where you'd like to meet, when you'd like to meet, and what you'd like to do during meetings.

Urban Growler is woman owned (yay!) and has good food (so you can definitely participate without drinking). There's no cost for the meetup itself, but you do need to cover your own tab. Urban Growler is located in St Paul, but it's very close to Minneapolis.

We're excited to meet you!

title: Monthly R Ladies Meeting: R package development!
description:
Create a package with RLadies!

Bring your laptop and we will walk through the steps to create a package.
We'll cover the tools you need to get started with package development, the requirements for creating a package, best practices, how to build in
automated testing and finally deploy and load your package.

If you haven't created a Github account yet and you want to see your package full circle, please create an account in advance.

We will use the following packages, so try to install these in advance to ensure you're ready to go!
devtools::install_g­ithub(“r-lib/devtools”)
install.packages(c(­“devtools”, “roxygen2”, “testthat”,
“knitr”,“usethis”,“­rstudioapi”,"tidyverse")­)

CONSUMING THINGS:
Just down the hall is a mini coffee shop. Feel free to bring snackies or beverages from home.

description:

Maybe you want to practice the skills learned in a previous meet-up or maybe you have your own R projects going (data analysis, programming, data viz, whatever!). Maybe you have a solo task or maybe you have a collaborator. Whatever your case may be, come work with some other R Ladies who will inspire you to focus and be super efficient!

We are trying out WeWork's space downtown. They are generously letting us use their space and providing us with high-speed wifi, coffee, tea, and water. You can bring food but not alcohol (probably not a surprise!). Definitely bring your own computer.

You will need to check in via the guest registration tablet at the front desk. Bring a photo ID and say you are my (Christina Knudson's) guest. After getting through registration, you can find us in room 40A.

title: Rondo Library Open Data Party
description:
The public library staff and city/county open data staff have been hosting events (“data parties”) this summer to talk about open data in Saint Paul! The goal is to bring data and data science into the broad umbrella of information you can find and use at the public libraries. This Thursday is the last one and it’s being hosted at Rondo Community Library! I’ll (the “citizen user” representative) be there on a panel with some of the open data staff to talk about community organizations, civic engagement, and data privacy. We’ve had kids come in the past too and they seem to enjoy it. There are snacks and lemonade, hope to see some of you there! There’ll be very little if any discussion of R, but I think the open data is interesting to know about anyway :)

If you’re taking the green line, it’s right by the Dale Street stop.

Link: https://sppl.org/data-party/

title: Monthly R Ladies Meeting: Writing websites in R with blogdown!
description:
This event is postponed again due to the weather forecast. Sorry for the inconvenience!

Create your own website with little or no html/css experience! We will go through the steps to launch and maintain your own static website using the R blogdown package. We will cover picking a theme, configuring, and launching your site, as well as a workflow for updates. We will also create a test blog using Rmarkdown (feel free to bring your own file.). This will be a hands-on working session, so please bring your laptop!

If you want to be ready for action:
-Make sure you have an account on either Github or Gitlab and configure it with RStudio (http://r-pkgs.had.co.nz/git.html) - we will show how to launch your site using these options
-Install the blogdown package in R using install.packages(“blogdown”­)

Get a 15-20 minute taste of some R topics!

We have 3 great R ladies lined up:
-Joan Hinrichs: Methods for analyzing healthcare utilization and cost in R
-Sarah Tonn: R road map to Real World Data (RWD)
-Wei Zang: The reticulate package - using Python in R

title: (VIRTUAL) Multilevel Modeling w/ MN Public Salaries Data
description:
It’s easy to get pretty far learning R and basic statistical analysis without really encountering the concept of multilevel modeling. This is unfortunate, because multilevel modeling can be a useful tool when data generating processes are hierarchical in nature--a situation which can be quite common in social, ecological, and political systems.

Alison Link will explore some of the multilevel modeling techniques and philosophies discussed in the book "Statistical Rethinking" by Richard McElreath, and explore how these concepts can be applied to a public salaries dataset on Minnesota state employees. The goal? Learn something new about about multilevel modeling AND generate some interesting findings about Minnesota state employee compensation!

title: (VIRTUAL) April Meetup: Topological Data Analysis
description:
Cheyanne Simpson and Maria Neuzil will introduce us to topological data analysis and guide us through some TDA basics in R.

Maria and Cheyanne are students at the University of St. Thomas. They conducted research under Prof Rebecca Glover, a member of R Ladies TC. Cheyanne, Maria, and their collaborator won the 2019 Center for Applied Mathematics Summer Research Award.

title: R Ladies at Urban Growler
description: Join us for some socializing! Whether you have come to a dozen or zero meetups so far, we'd love to get to know you. We'll have our own space (the barrel room in back). There's no fee to attend, but you are in charge of paying for whatever you consume. Urban Growler has great beer, food, and sodas.

title: Building and using lmeresampler for hierarchical linear models
description: Jenna K. spent the summer of 2020 working on the R package lmeresampler (https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/lmeresampler/index.html). During this meetup, Jenna will describe hierarchical linear models, the package's functions, the changes in package dependencies and parallelization that she implemented to streamline the code, and why she and her advisor chose to make those updates.

title: Dazzling HTML Reports
description:
Use R to combine documentation, analysis, and presentation into one highly efficient reporting mechanism! You'll never want to go back to the old ways of doing things once you see how simple it is to set up a reporting template. Lindsey D. will provide some essential packages, tips, and tricks based on her experience in this space.

You can find the materials for the talk here: https://github.com/iamaspacecoyote/rladies_dazzling_reports

title: Reap what you saw: unstructured HTML to presentable insights with rvest
description: Kristina M. will be presenting on the rvest package. rvest helps you scrape (or harvest) data from web pages!

title: Reproducible Research with groundhog
description: Tim S. will cover reproducible research processes and introduce us to the groundhog package (https://groundhogr.com/).

title: November Social
description:
Hi everyone!

It's been a long time since we got together. Let's reconnect!

This is an unsponsored event so you will be responsible for your own food and drink. Stormking has barbecue, beer, cocktails and non-alcoholic beverages.

COVID precautions:

* Stormking has both indoor and outdoor seating (with a couple firepits), so please feel comfortable to sit outside if that is your comfort level.
* Whether you plan to be inside or outside, PLEASE do not attend if you have a cough, fever, or any other COVID symptoms (regardless of the severity).

I hope to see you soon!

title: Box package
description:
Martha Eichlersmith will introduce us to the box package. The box package allows the user to create specific modules within their code. It's kind of like making mini-packages. The main perks of using box are 1. modular code without creating a full package and 2. limiting/organizing the name space.

Slides: [mareichler.github.io/rladies_box_intro](https://MarEichler.github.io/rladies_box_intro/)
Github Repo: [github.com/MarEichler/rladies_box_intro](https://github.com/MarEichler/rladies_box_intro)

title: R for Complete Newbies
description: This is for people BRAND NEW to R. I'll help you download and install R and RStudio. Then we will go through some of the basics. Don't be scared! We're a supportive, nonjudgmental crew. It's going to be great.

title: The Leap of Faith: Intro to Causal Inference
description: Lindsey will cover some background theory on causal inference and dive into a propensity score matching example using R. She would love for you to come and ask questions as this is prep for an upcoming presentation.

title: mix-R happy hour
description: We hope you all have taken some time to rest and recharge and are ready for an R ladies Twin Cities relaunch! Please join us for a casual happy hour to reconnect and to generate some topics for 2024 meetups. We hope to see you there.
